05280nam a22008055i 9780823296323DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20211998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232963237 a10.1515/97808232963232doi  a(DE-B1597)575264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0170002bisacsh1 aBristow, Edward W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Religion is an Island :bThe Nostra Aetate Dialogues /cEdward W. Bristow. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese dialogues began in 1993 as an outgrowth of a 1990 conference on Catholic-Jewish relations that commemorated the 25th anniversary of Nostra Aetate, the Vatican II document encouraging dialogue between the Catholic church and non-Christian religions. This volume contains a record of the first five Nostra Aetate dialogues, and it brings together an impressive array of Jewish and Catholic scholars. The conversations here take up "the Jewishness of Jesus" (John Meier and Shaye Cohen); "the Death of Jesus" (the late Raymond Brown and Michael Cook); "Catholic-Jewish Dialogue and the New Millennium" (Ismar Schorsch and John Cardinal O'Connor); "Jerusalem in Jewish and early Christian Thought" (Robert Wilkins and Michael Fishbane); and Abraham Joshua Heschel as "prophet of social activism" (Eugene Borowitz and Daniel Berrigan). Moderators and respondents include religion journalist Peter Steinfels, Rabbi Burton Visotzky and Susannah Heschel, Abraham Joshua Heschel's daughter. The volume is a solid introduction to some of the most important historical work on Christian origins, Jewish-Christian relations and the historical Jesus. The discussion of contemporary issues, especially between Brown and Cook and between Heschel and Berrigan, is lively and accessible. This collection serves as a model for interreligious dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aBerrigan, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorowitz, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Raymond E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardinal O’Connor, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Shaye J. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishbane, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHealey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHescher, Susannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeier, John P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Donald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Hare, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchorsch, Ismar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShcifer, Byron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinfels, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinfels, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVisotzky, Burton L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilken, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074